Bases of Contemporary US Primacy.</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Fellowship</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>ES/E02081X/1</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>&lt;p>International stability currently rests precariously on the high levels of material power enjoyed by the United States, coupled with relatively low recent levels of legitimacy in the exercise of that power. The major international political problem is to defuse the tension between the two. Traditionally, an international bargain has developed between the great powers and other states, according the former ?special rights and responsibilities?, since only the most powerful could provide the means to support a stable system. The weaker have been reassured by the equilibrium amongst the great powers. But at present, these checks and balances no longer exist. Can an acceptable hegemony be devised to replace that bargain? &lt;/p> 
&lt;p>This project seeks to resolve that problem at two levels. Theoretically, it elaborates a concept of hegemony based on consensus and social legitimacy. In policy terms, it applies this concept to those practical measures needed to make it attainable. These measures will be explored in a series of workshops bringing together international relations theorists, area specialists and practitioners, to investigate the bases of legitimate hegemony from a regional perspective, from within specific international organisations, and from the wider perspective of global civil society.&lt;/p></gtr:abstractText><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2010-09-30</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE"><gtr:id>924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE</gtr:id><gtr:name>ESRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2007-10-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>INCOME_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>331516</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs/><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs/><gtr:impactSummaryOutputs/><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs/><gtr:productOutputs/><gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutputs/><gtr:researchMaterialOutputs/><gtr:softwareAndTechnicalProductOutputs/><gtr:spinOutOutputs/></gtr:output><gtr:publications><gtr:publication><gtr:id>BCE9459A-FA42-492A-8C70-745F85F05129</gtr:id><gtr:title>Democracy in International Society: Promotion or Exclusion?</gtr:title><gtr:parentPublicationTitle>Millennium: Journal of International Studies</gtr:parentPublicationTitle><gtr:authors><gtr:author url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/baa6aaa25574751e8d422b80c8a54b39"><gtr:id>baa6aaa25574751e8d422b80c8a54b39</gtr:id><gtr:otherNames>Clark I</gtr:otherNames></gtr:author></gtr:authors><gtr:date>2009-01-01</gtr:date><gtr:outcomeId>doi_53cfa9fa994f1c19</gtr:outcomeId></gtr:publication><gtr:publication><gtr:id>46D